    "transcriptLines": [["00:00","00:07","Section 3."],["00:07","00:14","You will hear a discussion between two students called Mark and Fran about their presentation on some dolphins which are unique to New Zealand."],["00:14","00:18","on some dolphins which are unique to New Zealand."],["00:18","00:25","First, you have some time to look at questions 21 to 24 on page 5."],["00:48","01:03","Now listen carefully and answer questions 21 to 24."],["01:03","01:05","Hi Mark, thanks for coming around."],["01:05","01:07","Hi Fran, no problem."],["01:07","01:10","We need to try and get this presentation finished."],["01:10","01:13","Mark, let's start with the way dolphins make sounds."],["01:13","01:17","Well we all know that dolphins make clicking noises to communicate."],["01:17","01:24","Yes, they have tongues and larynxes as humans do, but what's really strange about the dolphin is that the sounds are focused through an extraordinary organ called the melon, <span class='answer-highlight'>which most other sea mammals don't have</span>."],["01:24","01:28","which most other sea mammals don't have."],["01:28","01:31","So shall I take over from there and speak about the different dolphin types?"],["01:31","01:36","I want to share what we found out about those rare dolphins that are special just to New Zealand in particular."],["01:36","01:43","Yeah, great, put the emphasis on them."],["01:43","01:46","The rarest of all is the Hector's dolphin, isn't it?"],["01:46","01:49","They are in danger, aren't they?"],["01:49","01:51","I think that's mainly because so many of them get tangled up in fishing gear,"],["01:51","01:56","especially gill nets and die."],["01:56","01:58","I know that some conservationists are worried about the impact of the tourism industry on dolphin numbers,"],["01:58","02:04","<span class='answer-highlight'>but I don't think that's a problem yet here</span>."],["02:04","02:07","Also, remember that this species has a very long reproductive cycle,"],["02:07","02:12","so their numbers don't get replenished quickly."],["02:12","02:15","Yeah, that's really sad."],["02:15","02:17","But at least the New Zealand government established a sanctuary for them, didn't it?"],["02:17","02:21","The fishing industry was against it, but I remember reading that the general public"],["02:21","02:26","were very supportive of the decision."],["02:26","02:28","<span class='answer-highlight'>It was a consequence of a study done by some marine biologists</span>."],["02:28","02:33","Having a protected breeding area has made a big difference to the dolphin population already."],["02:33","02:38","Yeah, I think their numbers have swelled to over 7,000 in total,"],["02:38","02:42","with a tiny group of just 89 living down off Southland,"],["02:42","02:45","nearly 2,000 living near Christchurch on the East Coast"],["02:45","02:48","<span class='answer-highlight'>and the biggest groups surviving off the West Coast</span>."],["02:48","02:51","It's pretty wild country over there, so I guess there aren't as many tourists and fishermen to disturb them."],["02:51","02:58","Before you hear the rest of the discussion,"],["03:00","03:03","you have some time to look at questions 25 to 30 on page 6."],["03:33","03:44","Now listen and answer questions 25 to 30."],["03:47","03:51","Okay, so how do you suggest I structure my part of the talk?"],["03:51","03:54","Well, you could start with the common dolphin,"],["03:54","03:57","<span class='answer-highlight'>which inhabits the whole of the sea around New Zealand</span>."],["03:57","04:01","And once you've covered everything to do with them, feeding and so on,"],["04:01","04:03","you go on to the more unusual types."],["04:03","04:10","The dusky dolphin is especially interesting because you know how all the dolphins travel in small social groups called pods?"],["04:10","04:15","<span class='answer-highlight'>Well, the dusky dolphins travel in pods as big as 800 members</span>."],["04:15","04:20","And I think the duskies like to travel along beside fishing and tourist boats, don't they?"],["04:20","04:26","<span class='answer-highlight'>Whereas the Hector's dolphins are different in that they prefer to go in the wake of boats, that is, coming along in the rear</span>."],["04:26","04:29","Yeah, they do. But they also dive down deep to avoid fast boats."],["04:29","04:34","Oh, let's not forget the Maui because they are endangered too aren't they?"],["04:34","04:39","<span class='answer-highlight'>There are only 150 of them left and they inhabit only the western coastal waters of the North Island of New Zealand</span>."],["04:39","04:47","Yeah, it's a pity. They also face problems because of their tiny size."],["04:47","04:52","Now the Orca is actually a dolphin too, right?"],["04:52","04:55","Yes, surprisingly. So I'll include that in my talk."],["04:55","04:59","People call them killer whales, but in fact they're not whales."],["04:59","05:03","They're a huge and very fierce type of dolphin."],["05:03","05:06","<span class='answer-highlight'>In New Zealand, Kaikoura in the South Island is the best place to spot Orca swimming by</span>."],["05:06","05:12","So people mistakenly think that's where they live."],["05:12","05:15","But actually Orcas cover vast distances."],["05:15","05:18","Let's not forget to mention the bottle-nose."],["05:18","05:21","<span class='answer-highlight'>It's bigger than nearly all the other dolphins, even the common dolphin</span>."],["05:21","05:25","Oh, but still not as big as the Orca, right?"],["05:25","05:28","That's right."],["05:28","05:29","Well, I think that's our presentation done now."],["05:29","05:32","That is the end of section three."],["05:34","05:37","You now have half a minute to check your answers."],["05:37","05:41","Now turn to section four on page seven."]],
